  "prompt": "Do all jobs in science require chemistry and physics? What if I just like biology?",
  "response": "Not all careers in science require in-depth knowledge of chemistry and physics. Many science-related jobs primarily focus on biology, though an understanding of chemistry and physics can be helpful in some cases. Here are several careers in biology that may interest you:\n\n1. **Microbiologist** - Studying microorganisms, such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites.\n2. **Ecologist** - Researching ecosystems, interactions among organisms, and environmental impacts.\n3. **Geneticist** - Focusing on genes, heredity, and genetic variation in living organisms.\n4. **Wildlife Biologist** - Studying animals and wildlife and their interactions with ecosystems.\n5. **Marine Biologist** - Researching marine organisms and ocean ecosystems.\n6. **Botanist** - Studying plant life and development.\n7. **Conservation Biologist** - Working to protect and manage biodiversity and natural resources.\n8. **Biotechnologist** - Using biological processes in industrial and other applications.\n9. **Medical Researcher** - Studying diseases, treatment, and advancements in medicine.\n10. **Evolutionary Biologist** - Researching the evolution of organisms and their genetic changes over time.\n\nCertain areas in biology, such as molecular biology or biochemistry, do involve chemistry, but many jobs that emphasize fieldwork, organismal biology, or ecology may require far less chemistry and physics.\n\nIt's important to explore different aspects of biology to find the niche that suits your interests best. This could involve taking different biology courses, participating in internships, joining clubs or organizations related to your field of interest, or talking to professionals working in those areas.",
